shipmentComments:
"They are BEAUTIFULLY packaged, thank you. Julie Lane"
Janelle- Everything looks great except for one sample, 6069, appears to be contaminated at all loci.  I made genotype calls for this sample, as there are strong signals for one individual and very faint signals for a second individual.  In addition, I repeated one of the loci (from original tube of DNA) to make sure I did not introduce contamination when transferring a portion of the DNA to a 96 well plate prior to setting up the PCR reactions.  
 
We would not ordinarily release data from contaminated DNA; you will have to decide if you feel comfortable using these data.
correctiveAction:
I just discovered that I made an incorrect call for HLA-C in sample 6077 (C*0303 instead of C*0304); our software called a very faint probe positive and I did not catch it until just now as I was carefully comparing adjacent strips to see if I could track down the source of contamination in 6069.  As Janelle always says, the software doesn’t know anything but pixels, it takes a human to make the correct call.  My deepest apologies for not catching the error before sending out the data.
 
Attached is the revised data, and sorry for the confusion.
 
Best regards,
 
Julie

proj_ID: High resolution HLA typing
shipmentComments:
Shipment 8A:

Ten samples worked well.
Sample 6019 was faint, and we were not able to call the class I loci. We were able to make calls for class II, although the DQA1 data are VERY faint. However, what we can see for DQA1 fits very well with the data for DRB1 and DQB1 and creates common, highly-conserved haplotypes, so we have high confidence in the calls.
Sample 6004 has alleles characteristic of both Hispanic and Asian populations, so we are curious as to whether this sample may originate from a person of mixed ethnicity.

Shipment 8B:

All samples worked well.
For sample 6053, the DRB1 data had one probe that was a bit faint, leading to a question of whether the DRB1*08xx allele is 0801 or 0803. We have called it DRB1*0803 and are reasonably confident with the call. We just wanted to note the small possibility that the DRB1 genotype may be DRB1*0801, 1501, rather than DRB1*0803, 1501 that we called.
correctiveAction: Take aliquot for gel analysis from dilution made for HLA so that one is testing the dilution as well as the procedure. Update SOP to include.
